# Battleship — Naval Command

A full-stack Battleship game built with PHP, MySQL, and vanilla JavaScript. Play against a hunt/target AI or go head-to-head with a friend in local 2-player mode. Features persistent player stats, a leaderboard, and a REST API with authenticated test endpoints for automated grading.

**Live Site:** http://lightslategray-dogfish-869967.hostingersite.com/

---

## Project Overview

Battleship — Naval Command is a web-based implementation of the classic Battleship board game. Players deploy a fleet of 5 ships (Carrier, Battleship, Cruiser, Submarine, Destroyer) on a 10×10 grid, then take turns firing at the opponent's board to sink their fleet.

The game supports two modes: a single-player mode against a computer opponent that uses a hunt/target AI strategy, and a local two-player mode with handoff screens to keep each player's board hidden between turns. Player statistics (wins, losses, total moves) are stored persistently in a MySQL database, and a leaderboard tracks all-time records. Game state is also saved to localStorage so that a browser refresh doesn't lose an in-progress match.

A separate REST API layer was built to support automated grading, with authenticated test-mode endpoints that allow deterministic ship placement, board inspection, game resets, and turn control.

---

## Architecture Summary

The frontend (`index.php`, `script.js`, `styles.css`) runs in the browser and handles the UI, ship placement, and sending shots via AJAX.

The backend has two layers. `game.php` powers the browser game using PHP sessions for in-game state and writes results to MySQL on game over. `api.php` is a separate stateless REST API that stores everything in the database directly — this is what the autograder hits.

```
Browser ──AJAX──► game.php ──► $_SESSION + MySQL
Grader  ──HTTP──► api.php  ──► MySQL
```

---

## API Description

The REST API (`api.php`) supports player creation, game creation, joining games, placing ships, and firing shots. All requests and responses are JSON.

Test-mode endpoints (`/test/games/{id}/ships`, `/test/games/{id}/board`, `/test/games/{id}/reset`, `/test/games/{id}/set-turn`) require an `X-Test-Mode` header and return 403 without it. These allow the grader to place ships deterministically, inspect board state, reset games, and control turns.

